TY  - JOUR
T1  - Toward an Empirical Prioritization of Contingency Variables for Business Strategy
AU  - Hambrick, Donald C.
AU  - Lei, David
Y1  - 1985/12/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256236
DO  - 10.5465/256236
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 763
EP  - 788
VL  - 28
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study, based on data from the Profit Impact of Market Strategies (PIMS) program, is a preliminary attempt to prioritize contingency variables for the field of business strategy. Chow tests for structural homogeneity shed light on the relative degrees of overall significance of ten widely-cited contingency variables. User sector, consumer or industrial, was the contingency variable that emerged as most potent among those examined. Implications for researchers and executives are suggested.
AB  - This study, based on data from the Profit Impact of Market Strategies (PIMS) program, is a preliminary attempt to prioritize contingency variables for the field of business strategy. Chow tests for structural homogeneity shed light on the relative degrees of overall significance of ten widely-cited contingency variables. User sector, consumer or industrial, was the contingency variable that emerged as most potent among those examined. Implications for researchers and executives are suggested.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256236
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256236
Y2  - 2026/04/24
